.TH EQUINOX 7 "2025-12-19" "Equinox Framework 1.0" "Equinox Framework Manual"
.SH NAME
equinox \- lightweight modular C framework for building extensible applications
.SH DESCRIPTION
Equinox is a comprehensive C framework for building modular, extensible applications with built-in HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2 server support. It provides a complete application lifecycle management system, module dependency resolution, service controllers, and concurrent connection handling.
.SH ARCHITECTURE
The Equinox Framework consists of the following core components:
.TP
.B Application
The main container that manages the lifecycle of modules and services. Provides initialization, startup, and shutdown coordination.
.TP
.B Modules
Reusable functional components with lifecycle callbacks (init, start, stop, cleanup) and dependency management. Modules can declare dependencies on other modules.
.TP
.B Service Controllers
Request/response handlers that expose named operations. Services can be registered with an application and participate in the application lifecycle.
.TP
.B HTTP Server
Full-featured web server supporting HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2 with:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
EPOLL-based concurrent connection handling (up to 1000 connections)
.IP \(bu 2
Path parameters with dynamic route matching (/api/users/:id)
.IP \(bu 2
Query string parsing with URL decoding
.IP \(bu 2
Non-blocking I/O with edge-triggered notifications
.IP \(bu 2
Automatic HTTP/2 protocol detection and negotiation
.IP \(bu 2
Binary framing and HPACK header compression for HTTP/2
.RE
.SH LIFECYCLE FLOW
A typical Equinox application follows this lifecycle:
.PP
.nf
1. Framework Init
2. Application Create
3. Register Modules and Services
4. Application Initialize (calls module/service init)
5. Application Start (calls module/service start)
6. [Application Running - Process Requests]
7. Application Stop (calls service/module stop)
8. Application Cleanup
9. Framework Shutdown
.fi
